'''Doughfaces''' was a term used in a disparaging context to describe Northerners in the United States in the years leading up to the Civil War who espoused sympathies with the Southern Slave Power. A Doughface would most likely be Northern Democrats who were more allied with the ideology of Southern Democrats than the majority of Northerners.  

Examples of Doughfaces include Franklin Pierce and James Buchanan, both Presidents during the time period 1853-1861, and people like Fernando Wood, mayor of New York City and U.S. Congressman.  These people supported the Southern agenda of the free expansion of slavery into the territories.  Unlike Democrats such as Stephen Douglas, who felt that Popular Soveriegnty should be the law of the land.  

The main reason there existed Northerners so closely linked with the Southern cause was fear of yet another sectional crisis, which turned out to be inevitable.


